<p style=3D"text-align:center;">A=C3=97A<sup>-1</sup> =3D A<sup>-1</sup>=C3=
=97A =3D I, where <b><i>I</i></b> is the identity matrix</p>
<p><b>Identity matrix:</b></p>
<p>The identity matrix is a square matrix with "1" across its diagonal, and=
 "0" everywhere else. The identity matrix is the matrix equivalent of the n=
umber "1." For example, the number 1 multiplied by any number <b><i>n</i></=
b> equals <b><i>n</i></b>. The same is true of an identity matrix multiplie=
d by a matrix of the same size: <b><i>A =C3=97 I =3D A</i></b>. Note that a=
n identity matrix can have any square dimensions. For example, all of the m=
atrices below are identity matrices. From left to right respectively, the m=
atrices below are a <b><i>2 =C3=97 2</i></b>, <b><i>3 =C3=97 3</i></b>, and=
